    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="97"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d97">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/1804½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">8 July, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: My clear judgment about
                        this<note n="1" xml:id="d97fn1">See Secretary Lansing’s letter of June 14,
                        1918, <ref target="#pg_130">p. 130</ref>.</note> is, that it is not wise to
                    take such action piecemeal about the items of a final settlement. Our attitude
                    is clearly spoken by our actions. The world has no doubt where we stand, and we
                    have already recognized the representatives of a Polish State. If we are to be
                    definite in the case of this particular national aspiration, why not in the case
                    of others, and where shall we stop, definition being at each step increasingly
                    difficult.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
